European Defence and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the Nazi occupation.
It may be due to the experience of living in a country at the heart of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations in Europe for centuries.
Perhaps all these factors, combined together, have led me to the conviction that Europe represents a single political entity, whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could forever be two Europes  one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and the other less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated  is a mistake.
That's like heating part of a room while the other part remains cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its differences.
Every significant event elicits an echo across Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to incorporate the new post-communist democracies  which is in Europe's interest , a number of essential tasks must be addressed, both within the new democracies and within the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must promote the community spirit in post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a living society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies become an organic part of a shared continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more interconnected they are, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to entrust diverse solidarity tasks to self-managed institutions and nonprofit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economical it will be; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to people or their associations.
Authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that can only be exercised by states.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy, with its abandonment of European solidarity, which led to the Munich capitulation.
This experience is still a strong call to remain vigilant.
One must confront evil as soon as it appears; however, it is not enough if only governments act.
For government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern for safety is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is intensively working on a new concept for its security policy.
It should be characterized by the ability to make quick decisions and swiftly implement collective decisions—reforms that have proven necessary in light of the recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom, as well as the concerns of pan-European security, require interventions beyond the EU's borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where the UN mandate might not come, even though an intervention would be in the interest of many people, all of Europe, yes, even human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical preparedness.
However, further measures are still needed in the area of preventive security, but it is also essential that this security reflects the values of the expanded European civil society.
Tens of thousands of human lives and an enormous amount of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of the former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the onset of the conflicts.
Despite warnings of impending horror, they acted only timidly.
These failures were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot depend on the USA forever, especially when it comes to European issues.
It must be able to understand its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can remain a respected part of the world order if it proves incapable of agreeing on means and methods to protect human rights, not only within its territory but also in regions that may one day join it.
Such an EU expansion is only justifiable if it proceeds hand in hand with a courageous reform of EU institutions.
I hope confidently that the government conference on institutional reform will present feasible proposals to advance the Union.
But I see this as the beginning of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a permanent commitment to accelerate and make EU decision-making more transparent.
A point related to the institutional reform is the question of how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not simply be outvoted by the larger ones, while still duly taking into account the size of individual states.
One possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber will not be directly elected, but rather chosen from their own ranks by the parliaments of the member states.
The first chamber of the EU—that is, the current parliament—would thus reflect the size of the individual member states, while the second chamber, with the same number of representatives for each state, would enhance equality.
Sooner or later, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution—a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution requires two parts.
Part one would define the rights and obligations of both European citizens and the states, the underlying values, and the significance and objectives of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their principal competences, and their relations with each other.
Such a basic law would not automatically convert the current union into the federal superstate feared by Euroskeptics.
It would, however, help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, to understand it better, to see its significance for their lives, and, consequently, to identify with it.
